                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-15T12:27:45.930-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Carolyn Groves, a devoted mother and now former nurse from Perth, Australia, is one of many women who saw everyday life upended when she received her diagnosis of late-stage ovarian cancer in 2022.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Within weeks of receiving the news, Carolyn went from working 10-hour days in a hospital to suddenly losing her independence, career and social life.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“I used to be someone who was a volunteer in the community, somebody that was looking after others, and being a support person for my family. But now all the roles have reversed,” she said.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Carolyn’s journey since has been marked not just by physical changes, such as hair loss and fatigue, but also mental, emotional and social ones. Such challenges are not uncommon among the estimated 600,000 women living with ovarian cancer.&lt;sup>1&lt;/sup> Their experiences underscore the need for greater access and support for patients, and AbbVie’s commitment to research in oncology, which aims to improve outcomes and quality of life for patients living with difficult-to-treat cancers.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
                            <quote
                                cq:styleIds="[1000000000000]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2025-09-15T12:27:55.487-04:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="VALENSX5"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-15T12:28:56.423-04:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/quote"
                                attributionName="Carolyn Groves"
                                attributionTitle="Ovarian cancer patient"
                                dmPresetType="imagePreset"
                                quote="It would be really nice if there were ways to diagnose us quickly, have treatment earlier and cures so that we can carry on our role in society."
                                quoteType="regular"
                                textSize="h0"/>
                        </par_12>
