                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <text2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-15T12:33:28.014-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Shifting from her role as a person supporting other people, both as a nurse and as a mother, to being the one needing support has also changed the dynamics of a lot of relationships, Carolyn says.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“As a parent it’s been very, very hard for my children that I’m no longer the same mother. Even though they’re grown men, I’m no longer the capable mother that’s there to support them in the same way I used to be able to,” she says.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2025-09-15T12:33:33.896-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-15T12:33:33.896-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-15T12:33:50.156-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Shifting careers and roles in the workplace  "
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-19T17:04:55.220-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Along with affecting relationships, an ovarian cancer diagnosis can affect a woman’s ability to work. Because care plans can often involve multiple rounds of chemotherapy or other therapies, surgery, hospital visits or extended time away are all too common.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Taking time to get to and from appointments, receive treatment and recuperate from that treatment can cause many women to miss days or weeks of work or require them to quit working all together. Carolyn is one of many who found herself too ill to work, requiring her to leave her nursing career.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“Ovarian cancer takes many of us out in the prime of our lives, when we should still be working and should still be looking after our families,” she says.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“Instead of having us being a burden in the community because we're unwell, it would be really nice if there were ways to diagnose us quickly, have treatment earlier and cures so that we can carry on our role in society.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Stories like Carolyn’s inspire AbbVie’s research in oncology, which aims to improve outcomes and quality of life for patients living with difficult-to-treat cancers. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.abbvie.com/science/areas-of-focus/oncology.html&quot;>Learn more about our research&lt;/a>.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator_2037335802
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2025-09-15T12:37:20.864-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-15T12:37:20.864-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <text2_copy_1319269347
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-09-15T12:35:34.739-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>&lt;b>References&lt;/b>&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;ol>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Reid, F., Bhatla, N., Oza, A. M., Blank, S. V., Cohen, R., Adams, T., Benites, A., Gardiner, D., Gregory, S., Suzuki, M., &amp;amp; Jones, A. (2020). The World Ovarian Cancer Coalition Every Woman Study: identifying challenges and opportunities to improve survival and quality of life.&amp;nbsp;&lt;i>International Journal of Gynecologic Cancer&lt;/i>,&amp;nbsp;&lt;i>31&lt;/i>(2), 238–244. &lt;a href=&quot;https://doi.org/10.1136/ijgc-2019-000983&quot;>https://doi.org/10.1136/ijgc-2019-000983&lt;/a>&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Luvero, D., Plotti, F., Aloisia, A., Montera, R., Terranova, C., Carlo De Cicco Nardone, Scaletta, G., Lopez, S., Miranda, A., Capriglione, S., Gatti, A., Pierluigi Benedetti Panici, &amp;amp; Angioli, R. (2019). Ovarian cancer relapse: From the latest scientific evidence to the best practice.&amp;nbsp;&lt;i>Critical Reviews in Oncology/Hematology&lt;/i>,&amp;nbsp;&lt;i>140&lt;/i>, 28–38. &lt;a href=&quot;https://doi.org/10.1016/j.critrevonc.2019.05.014&quot;>https://doi.org/10.1016/j.critrevonc.2019.05.014&lt;/a>&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/ol>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&lt;b>Media inquiries:&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa; &lt;/b>&lt;a href=&quot;mailto:abbviemediarelations@abbvie.com&quot;>abbviemediarelations@abbvie.com&lt;/a>&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
